---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
---
<Base title="Metrics That Move Nothing" section={2}>
  <SectionHeader n={2} title="Metrics That Move Nothing" meta="~500w" />

  <div class="prose">

    <p>
      There is a difference between a number and a signal. A number tells you a value.
      A signal tells you whether to act. Most dashboards are entirely full of numbers.
      Almost none of them contain signals.
    </p>

    <p>
      Revenue this month: $4.2M. Is that good? Compared to what? The budget? Last year?
      Last month, seasonally adjusted? Is the number trending in the right direction?
      Is the direction of the trend accelerating or slowing? Does it matter? Should you
      do anything about it right now, or wait? The number tells you none of this.
      It is just a value, suspended in a frame, wearing the aesthetic of insight.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      <p>A number tells you a value. A signal tells you whether to act.
      Most dashboards are full of numbers with no signals.</p>
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      This is the metric design problem nobody talks about. We obsess over data freshness,
      query performance, visualisation choice. We hold long arguments about whether a bar
      chart or a line chart better represents the data. We debate whether to use absolute
      values or percentage changes. And then we display the result with no context,
      no threshold, no indication of whether this particular value on this particular day
      should cause anyone to do anything at all.
    </p>

    <p>
      Vanity metrics are the most common offender. Pageviews. Follower counts. App
      downloads. Total registered users. These numbers go up and to the right, reliably,
      and the people on whose dashboards they live feel a quiet satisfaction each morning
      when they check. But none of these numbers are close enough to a decision to be
      useful. They tell you something happened. They do not tell you whether the thing
      that happened matters or what you should do differently because of it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Activity metrics are the subtler version of the same problem. Tickets closed.
      Emails sent. Support conversations resolved. These feel operational — they feel
      like the kinds of things a well-run team should track. And perhaps they should
      be tracked, internally, by the teams responsible for them. But they have no place
      on a leadership dashboard unless there is a specific decision attached. "How many
      tickets did we close?" is not a decision. "Should we hire another support engineer
      before Q3?" — that is a decision. The ticket volume is one input into it. It belongs
      in that context, or it belongs nowhere.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="The signal test">
      For any metric on your dashboard: what value would cause you to do something
      differently? If you cannot answer, the metric is not a signal. It is wallpaper.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      The real problem is that collecting metrics is easy and designing signals is hard.
      A signal requires you to know what threshold matters, which means you need to have
      thought clearly about what you are trying to do. It requires you to have committed
      to a response — if this number drops below X, we will do Y. That commitment is
      uncomfortable because it forces accountability in advance. So instead, organisations
      collect numbers and call it measurement.
    </p>

    <p>
      A dashboard full of signals would look almost nothing like what most teams ship.
      It would have fewer panels, each with explicit thresholds. It would show context —
      the same number in relation to a target, a prior period, an external benchmark.
      It would be calibrated to a specific decision cadence: what choices do we make
      daily, weekly, quarterly, and what data informs each? It would have almost no
      activity metrics and no vanity metrics. It would probably fit on half a screen.
    </p>

    <p>
      The reason most dashboards are not built this way is that building it this way
      requires answering hard questions before you open a single chart tool. Most
      organisations are not ready for that conversation. So they skip it, and build
      something that looks like measurement without performing any of its function.
    </p>

  </div>
</Base>
